
<appendix xml:id="set-theory">
  <title>Naive Set Theory</title>
    <introduction><p>A review of basic results concerning sets.</p></introduction>
<definition>
  <ul>
    <li><m>\mb R</m> is the set of real numbers.</li>
    <li><m>\mb Z</m> is the set of integers.</li>
    <li>
      <m>\mb N=\setBuilder{z\in\mb Z}{z\geq 0}=\setList{0,1,2,\dots}</m>
      is the set of natural numbers, including zero.
    </li>
    <li>
      <m>\mb Q=\setBuilder{\frac{z}{n+1}}{z\in\mb Z,n\in\mb N}</m>
      is the set of rational numbers.
    </li>
  </ul>
</definition>
<theorem>
<p>
  The <term>Archemedian Property</term> of the real numbers guarantees that
  for each real number <m>x\in\mb R</m>, there exists a natural number
  <m>n\in\mb N</m> such that <m>\frac{1}{n}\lt x</m>.
</p>
</theorem>
<theorem>
<p>
  <term>De Morgan's Laws</term>: Let <m>\mc A</m> be a collection of subsets of
  <m>X</m>.
</p>
<me>X\setminus\bigcup_{A\in\mc A}A=\bigcap_{A\in\mc A}(X\setminus A)</me>
<me>X\setminus\bigcap_{A\in\mc A}A=\bigcup_{A\in\mc A}(X\setminus A)</me>
</theorem>
</appendix>

